0 A few miles outside Stratford-upon-Avon, on the banks of the river Stour in the heart of Shakespeare country, sits a spectacular neo-Gothic mansion called Ettington Park.
0 In 40 acres of parkland and filled with suits of armour, oil paintings and a selection of resident ghosts, the stately home is the family seat of 58-year-old Philip Shirley.
0 You probably haven't heard of Mr Shirley, a tall, somewhat shy accountant with a wife and four children, who inherited a large tranche of Warwickshire on the death of his father, Major John, in 2009.
1 This unassuming multi-millionaire is by many measures the most impeccably bred landowner in the country.
0 A cousin by marriage to David Cameron, he is almost the only person in England whose can trace his lineage back to the Domesday Book by uninterrupted male descent.
0 Shirley's paternal ancestors have managed to hold land continuously in the 'manor' where Ettington Hall stands for almost a thousand years.
0 So evocative is the family history that William Shakespeare, an occasional house-guest at Ettington Park, wrote gushingly about 'the spirit of valiant Shirley'.
0 Today, some 400 years later, talk of that 'valiant' spirit brings a wry smile to the lips of local people.
1 For Philip Shirley finds himself at the centre of a very public skirmish.
0 It revolves around some six acres of farmland that he owns on the edge of Ettington, a couple of miles from the family seat.
0 This site — a field crossed by a well-trodden footpath, with views of the Cotswold Hills — is the subject of a fierce planning dispute.
0 Shirley, in partnership with a building company, plans to develop it to create several dozen 'executive' homes.
1 Ill-feeling over the proposal has united the local community in opposition.
0 More than 400 people — one for every house in Ettington — have filed written objections to it.
0 Many see it as emblematic of a wider national malaise.
0 For as the Campaign to Protect Rural England (CPRE) revealed this week, a staggering 729,000 homes are to be built on greenfield sites such as this.
0 Almost 200,000 of those will be on supposedly protected Green Belt land.
