0 The battle has not just divided the village but caused tensions among the members of Shirley's immediate family.
0 Indeed, I understand that his wife, Augusta, is vehemently opposed to the development.
0 The trouble here began last year, when Philip Shirley struck a multi-million-pound deal to allow a developer, Charles Church Homes, to build 80 homes on the field, which has been in his family for generations.
0 Locals, when they found out in September, were outraged by the project, which would increase the size of the pretty village, which has two pubs and one shop, by a fifth.
0 They held angry public meetings, signed petitions, met politicians.
0 After a planning application was submitted last month, they began bombarding Stratford-upon-Avon's district council with complaints.
0 The village is dominated by banners and signs opposing the proposed estate, claiming that it will increase traffic, destroy a well-used footpath and place an intolerable strain on the local school.
0 'It's the scale that is so outrageous,' says Sally Rawles, the leader of SHAPE, a lobby group with 200 local members opposing the development.
0 'Stratford council have said our village should have no more than 50 new homes between now and 2031.
0 'This will give us 80 in one go, in a highly visible spot.
0 It will rip the heart out of our community.
0 It just makes my blood boil.'
0 Much personal anger is directed at Philip Shirley himself.
0 'We never thought the Shirleys would do something like this,' says Mary-Ann Warmington, 56, whose grandmother, a parlourmaid, was one of many locals who worked at Ettington Park.
