0 As regards the planning battle, though, similar disputes are playing out across rural Britain thanks to the housing boom, a loophole in planning regulations and the incompetence of more than half of our local authorities.
0 In at least eight villages around Stratford-upon-Avon, developments of between 20 and 100 homes are mooted.
0 Locals are calling it 'a battle for Shakespeare country'.
0 Some of the building applications go back to 2010, when the Government altered planning law to require every local authority to create a 'core strategy' outlining where an allotted number of new homes should be built in the coming years.
0 It was decreed that, if no such plan was in place, home-builders who were refused planning permission for a project but appealed against that decision to central government would be likely to gain automatic consent.
0 The rule was supposed to encourage local government bureaucrats to create housing plans promptly.
0 But three years after it came into operation, 178 of the country's 327 district councils still haven't managed to complete their 'core strategy' — temporarily giving developers carte blanche to build on almost any rural land they can buy.
0 As the CPRE revealed this week, 38 major developments, involving 8,700 new homes, were given the green light on appeal last year.
0 Most were in the constituencies of Tory MPs, leading some to wonder if anger over the issue could cost the party marginal seats at next year's election.
0 'There are lots of Tory landowners benefiting from this planning loophole,' says Sally Rawles.
0 'They all have connections to the party and many of them are donors.'
0 Which is awkward for the area's Tory MP, Nadhim Zahawi, who backs the project's opponents.
0 The other day Mr Zahawi, a No 10 policy adviser, published an open letter to the Government calling for the loophole to be closed.
0 It declared that the 'physical harm' being done by 'rapacious developers' threatens 'to become the defining legacy of this Government'.
0 He had a point.
0 For the longer the loophole remains open, the angrier the voters of Ettington, and many other villages, will surely get.
